sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1702002
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: E. coli fadD and fadL under control of lac promoter
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: fadL and fadD were extracted using genomic PCR from DH5alpha E. coli. The lac promoter was sourced from the iGEM distribution kit.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
Details about fadD: Acyl-CoA synthetase is the first enzyme the beta oxidation pathway. It attaches Coenzyme A to long chain fatty acids, allowing them to continue through the pathway. The transcription of fadD is controlled by the enzyme produced by fadR under standard conditions.
Details about fadL: LCFAs are naturally moved into E. coli by a long-chain fatty acid outer membrane porin, which is encoded for by fadL.
Detail about P_lac+fadD+fadL construct By placing both fadD and fadL under the control of an inducible promoter, we can control expression. The combination of fadD and fadL should greatly increase E. coli's uptake of fatty acids into the cell.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: The expression of fadD and fadL is inducible with lactose or IPTG.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Anthony Roulier, Chauncy Hinshaw, Krista Henderson

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K861500
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: FadL, Long-chain fatty acids transporter from E.coli str. K12
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: E.coli str. K.12 lab mutant DH5α
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Long-chain fatty acids are transported across the cell membrane via a transport/acyl-activation mechanism involving an outer membrane protein, FadL. The fadL gene codes for a 43,000-dalton membrane protein (FLP) which has been implicated as being essential for LCFA transport. And it is repressed by FadR.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Kuanwei Sheng

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K861010
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: FadD, an inner membrane-associated acyl-CoA synthase
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: E.coli str. K2 lab mutant DH5α
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: In Escherichia coli, LCFAs are transported and activated as fatty acyl-CoAs .The process of acetylation is catalyzed by FadD, the bacterial acyl-CoA synthetase (ACS).To enter the cell, MCFAs and LCFAs must be activated by theacyl-CoA synthetase (fadD gene product). And it is repressed by FadR
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Kuanwei Sheng

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0034
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Varies from -6 to +1 region from original sequence to accomodate BioBricks suffix.

No secondary structures are formed in the given RBS region. Users should check for secondary structures induced in the RBS by upstream and downstream elements in the +50 to -50 region, as such structures will greatly affect the strength of the RBS. Contact info for this part: Brian Chow
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Vinay S Mahajan, Voichita D. Marinescu, Brian Chow, Alexander D Wissner-Gross and Peter Carr IAP, 2003.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: LacI
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The Plac insert was PCR'd from the MG1655 strain of E.coli K12.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
Inverting regulatory region controlled by LacI (BBa_C0010, BBa_C0011, etc.)

The pLac regulatory region is a 243 base-pair sequence with standard BioBrick prefix and suffix sections on its ends. It contains two protein binding sites: CAP, which is generally present in E.coli and is assocciated with cell health and availability of glucose., and LacI, the Lac inhibitor BBa_C0010 which binds in an dimerized cooperative manner to inhibit the transcription of the protein that follows. In the presence of lactose or IPTG, an analog of lactose, LacI is unable to correctly bind and inhibit transcription. This allows BBa_R0010 to be used as a inverter or as a detector of lactose or IPTG.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: LacI binds to this regulator. This part is incompatible with species containing active LacI coding regions. Lactose and IPTG disable the operation of LacI and this regulator. This part is incompatible with environments containing lactose or lactose analogs.
